Women considered witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They usually have an advanced age, cannot work, for example, for health reasons, are single and have no children.
Women who "turn" witches are sent to an isolated area, so that they do not harm the rest of the village.
"Men seldom suffer such a thing."
“Young healthy women are also not isolated, because they help at work and have children,” explains a nun who, in the capital of the West African state Burkina Faso, is in a special residence of more than a hundred women expelled from their communities.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual “social measure”.
He issued an information booklet that should help avoid witch hunting.
However, this has a sticker.
“More than 70% of adults in Burkina Faso don’t know how to read,” warns Die Standard about the disadvantages of written awareness.
The accusations of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, neighbouring Burkina Faso, 72-year-old Ammy Hemmah died last week when three women and two men tortured her, covered her with gasoline and burned her.
The news appeared on the BBC.
The authors claim that it was due to an unfortunate aggregate of circumstances.
According to her version, the woman clinged to the oil used for ritual ointments.
He was caught in flames when the group wanted to “expulse the evil spirits” from the woman.
The isolation of “witches” is supported by people of all levels of education.
The newspaper Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old Burkina Faso businessman as saying: "The devourers of human souls have always represented a danger," he said.
While in Burkina Faso the government is trying to calm the witch hunt, in Gambia last year the president still participated in it.
“Gambian President Jammeh, after his aunt’s death, launched a wide-ranging witch hunt that allegedly had been related to his death and had attempted to kill the president himself through black magic.”
“To help him, he brought shamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, military and the president’s personal escort, were forced to bring randomly chosen men and women from among the Gambian peoples to the president’s property in Kanilai,” Amnesty International said in its report.
At the estate, the people arrested had to drink a pomegranate of herbs with hallucinogenic effects, which, in addition, caused them intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of the detainees did not survive the stay on the farm.
After international pressure, they finally released about a thousand people detained.
