Architects have understood that offices also need nursery
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
No one would say that he also hides in his interior a small kindergarten with everything he owns to such facilities: colored walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch.Design employees have been able to attend.
Architectural project company Arch.Design, from whose studio came out numerous well-known buildings in Brno, thought from the first drafts of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-guardianship.
The company employs around 90 people, mainly at the age of the baby boom, and wanted to allow architects and designers to return to work soon after motherhood.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, nursery is one of the benefits Arch.Design offers to its employees as part of its social program.
Builders and architects in this way have the opportunity to combine a demanding profession with the care of children.
The minigarden was an idea of the Arch.Designu employees themselves and, with the support of the management, managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company’s minigarden is financed through the European Social Fund under the Operational Programme for Human Resources and Employment, as well as the Czech Republic’s state budget.
Thanks to the funding granted (a grant of more than 2.8 million Czech kroner) they were able to buy the equipment and, after two years, hire qualified personnel and services.
When funding runs out (two years), Arch.Design is obliged to keep the mini-gardenhouse running with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project took one year and the company contributed to the submission of the funding application.
The care of children is in the hands of qualified staff; in addition, a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present all day for their care. The kindergarten currently accommodates children without age limits, although most of them are less than three years old.
Since it is a "mini-carriage", it can only accommodate up to five children simultaneously, although with turns they come more during the day.
The operation of the kindergarten is flexible to adapt to the needs of the parents and children of all workers have the same right to use the kindergarten, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although it is an individual education and care, the contents of the mini-guardianship program are comparable to the usual preschool education program.
In it, children not only play, but they also receive a quality teaching: from basic learning to school preparation, they teach English.
The class not only has toys and table games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself create a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go to see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up late school children when they are away from their workplace.
Parents are more productive while they work.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a loyalty relationship between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is placed among firms that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program strengthened staff marketing.
The house of the bones continues to fascinate after 100 years.
The roof looks like the lobe of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs resemble the column of a dinosaur, and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Due to its skeleton-like shape, the locals nicknamed it "the house of the bones".
Its organic shapes, its striking colors, the novel use of the stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade reminiscent of the scales and the smoothly curved lines, all this is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaudí.
The porch of the house plays with oniric lines, delicate colors and textures derived from nature and fauna.
Paying more attention, a certain geometry, rhythm and carefully thought order is observed.
At night, the entire facade of the house looks even more impressive, as it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
The serpent and the twisting of shapes still surprises us inside as well.
The corrugated wood copies the frames of the windows, curtains, door ornaments, mirrors and posters.
The Casa Batlló, located in the Eixample district at number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Gràcia, emerged from the remodeling of a 1877 house by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction took two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on demolishing the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí’s idea of making a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Casa Batlló, consisting of several apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
The architect Josep María Jujol collaborated on the design.
In fact, in their plans of the project appeared ornaments for the apartment representative of the owner of the property and the mosaics used in the façade.
In the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of the Casa Batlló was the beginning of Jujol’s successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Casa Mila and the Güell de Gaudí Park, in which there are other pieces of the same.
Due to its organic shape, the locals soon after its completion called it "the house of the bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows, began to call it "the house of the squirrels".
It is also said that, at the top of the construction, appears the sword of San Jorge, patron of Catalonia.
Other sculptural elements of construction conceal religious motives.
Gaudí projected in the house a unique system for the central heating era with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
It can be strange its inclination of forty-five degrees.
During the construction, Gaudí did not respect at all the construction norms of the time and was not influenced by them.
Still, the construction obtained the corresponding permission from the beginning, although obviously in it the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the town hall was so impacted by the result that it requested correction.
It bothered him, for example, that the construction included columns even to the public lane.
Arrangements were never made, rather the opposite: only fifteen days after the request of the town hall, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two tallest floors of the building.
In the lower floors the owner himself was installed.
In the gallery on the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry.
The six-storey house is completely crossed by a staircase leading to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all the angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked on the modern concept of connecting space.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the lounges and a larger group can communicate in this way smoothly, without giving up the privacy needed for more intimate conversations.
The house, with Gaudí's reconstruction, not only obtained a new façade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with the light, white and blue tiles covering the inner courtyard and sunglasses.
The game with the two colors provides the maximum of light on all floors of the house.
It was based simply on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which, on the contrary, absorb the rays of the sun.
Anyone can visit the House of Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and recharged apartment of the accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits confirmed, or discovered, that this is a very beneficial business and expanded the visits to the common area and the buhardilla, including the roof terrace.
The price of entry to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and holders of tourist cards get a 20% discount.
The amount significantly exceeds the entry price of Gaudí’s other buildings in the city.
