However, the mood varies considerably from country to country (see chart 4).
The good economic performance of Brazil and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a general sense of progress.
This feeling is less common in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more severe and violent crimes have increased.
For the second time since the surveys began, most surveyed in Latin America mention crime, rather than unemployment, as the most serious problem facing their country (see graph 5).
Approximately 31% say they or a close relative have been the victim of crime in the past year, a figure that has declined since 38% last year and is the lowest percentage recorded since 1995.
The most positive economic returns are reflected in greater support for private enterprises and the market economy: around 71% of respondents in the region say private enterprises are essential for development, while in 2007 it was only 56% (see graph 6).
Around 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow their country to develop, compared to 47% last year.
It is interesting that 62% of respondents in Venezuela believe the same thing (and 80% support private companies), although their leftist president, Hugo Chávez, is expropriating numerous private companies.
Brazil is the country with the highest leadership in the region, as indicated by 19% of respondents (against 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, the same figure as last year) and Venezuela (9% versus 11% a year ago).
