"This body has a double capacity."
"It can grow either with phosphorus or with arsenic."
“That makes it very peculiar, though little missing, to be a really ‘alien’ way of life,” said Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report appearing in the online edition of Thursday’s Science publication.
It has long been thought that there are six major elements essential to life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus, and sulfur.
However, researchers have found that the bacteria, found in Mono Lake, California, can continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
“It makes you stand out as much as possible,” said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
According to Anbar, the finding is important for the search for life on different planets on Earth, as researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know what it looks like.
The study focuses on a microbe discovered on Earth.
However, the convocation of a press conference to discuss the discovery, in which no details of the discovery were disclosed, generated a great deal of speculation on the Internet about the possibility that the report would indicate the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
He didn't.
What the discovery "shows is that in other planetary environments, there could be organisms that use other elements to boost their biochemistry and that the set of "standard" elements we consider indispensable to life might not be so fixed," said Charles Cockell, professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
“This work is novel because it demonstrates the substitution of one element for another in biochemistry and the basic biochemical structure,” Cockell added.
The discovery was not made by chance.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's astrobiology institute, who led the study, focused on Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are similar from a chemical point of view, so he speculated that a microbe exposed to both could replace one another.
“Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is similar to phosphorus.”
"As a result, it can be difficult for organisms to differentiate them."
“However, arsenic is different enough that it doesn’t work as well as phosphorus, so it enters and, in some way, appeals to biochemical machinery,” explains Anbar.
The researchers picked up the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which they managed to adapt and used to grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus, but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead poses the possibility that a form of life that uses arsenic can naturally exist, either in other parts of Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is most common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea that arsenic can be replaced with phosphorus is not new, but an example has never been found to prove it works.
Arsenic was more common in the early Earth eras, he noted, so researchers speculated that the early life forms may have used it.
“Yes, it suggests that there could be other means of generating life, not just the way life was formed on Earth in the past,” said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon’s research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
