A more moderate side of order maintenance is promoted in China
As an urban instructor sergeant, Tang Shenbin marked the passage on a square in the city, severely inspecting the nervous people in charge of him, issuing orders in a low voice with military authority.
He wanted the female members of Chengguan, the cowardly policemen of China’s urban order, fearful and despised for their captivating measures and their tendency to violence, to convey a certain impression to a handful of spectators.
"Signs!"
"Attention!"
Show them, he whispered, "How beautiful girls are!"
Four girls who barely passed their teenage years with white gloves and identical olive green jackets and adjusted pants to draw attention.
Four pairs of perfectly aligned black shoes.
Four stylish hats perfectly placed above the hair tied with blue and white stripes.
"Personally, I think they have a normal appearance," said Mr. Tang, disdainfully.
"Models are beautiful."
More than one government has tried to clear the image of China’s urban inspectors.
A city ordered all new recruits to have a degree.
The Guangdong Province changed the grey green color of uniforms to a supposedly more attractive blue.
Wuhan, in central China, replaced the use of force with intimidating glances: in 2009, according to a report, 50 officers surrounded a shelf of snack cart, and watched it with a sniffing eyebrow constantly for half an hour, until the street vendor picked up his stuff and left.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 inhabitants in Chengdu, has chosen a radical image change.
Since 2003, the district has added 13 women to its urban police, expressly chosen for their appearance, proportion and youth.
The idea is to give the police cough a softer, feminine side.
Unfortunately, even Scarlett Johansson would have to fight to increase China’s slightest respect for these city squadrons.
And for a good reason, critics would argue.
Unlike the police, these officers are only allowed to enforce city ordinances, imposing fines and other administrative penalties.
But the Chinese news media routinely portray a different reality.
In January 2008, inspectors in Hubei Province killed a transient after using their cell phone to film them while disbanding a protest against a garbage dump.
Last year, a Beijing inspector training manual was stolen and published on the internet, describing how to effectively beat criminals without causing them to bleed.
This year, a street vendor of sandwiches in Shanghai suffered brain damage after a line with five officers.
A violent video game, available for download online, features Chinese-trained inspectors attacking street vendors.
"Chengguan has left a scar on the government," China Daily, a national publication, lamented last year after another tactical controversy.
The newspaper called for “a really meticulous cleaning.”
Skeptics say the current approach is far from this.
After the district requested through a notice of eight new female recruits in October, an editorial in The Beijing Evening News asked whether women had real duties or were simply a scenic distraction.
The answer seems to be a bit of both.
The district’s announcement called for female candidates aged 18 to 22, with a good figure “and the five harmonious facial features”.
They should have a height above average, more than 1.6 meters or 5 feet, 2 1<0xE2><0x81><0x84>2 inches.
Retirement at the age of 26 is mandatory.
Officials said the work was physically too hard for women over the age of 25.
