"Very routine".
One reason is that female officers lack the power of their male counterparts to confiscate merchandise from sellers.
They can only threaten to report offenders to their male supervisors.
This tends to protect them from the sudden public demonstrations of animosity against the bureaucracy, which are common everywhere in China.
This year, hundreds of citizens in Kunming, the provincial capital of Yunnan, were mutined after spreading the false rumor that Chengguan officers had murdered a salesman.
More than a dozen Chengguan police officers were injured in the night episode; 14 government vehicles were shot or fired.
At the moment Xindu has avoided such violence.
But calmness is barely guaranteed.
Just two blocks from the peaceful Baoguang Square, where female officers patrolled that morning, more than 50 people gathered in a corner.
Officers had confiscated a motorcycle that was being repaired on the sidewalk rather than in a workshop, as required by the regulations.
The owner of the motorcycle screamed loudly.
The situation stagnated for 15 minutes before the officers, with a bad face, opened their elbows to their vehicles and quickly left with the motorcycle and their owner.
Li Xuedong, 40, a coordinator assigned to the male squad, remained behind, with his white badge turned to hide his name.
Like female officers, coordinators, men aged 40 or over, play a purely supportive role.
Unlike them, they are not taught to maintain an elegant image.
"Sometimes we fight verbally."
"Sometimes we fight physically," Mr. Li said with total naturalness.
“Most of the time, it’s the audience who starts the fight.”
