When Ensign spokesman Jennifer Cooper announced that Ensign was no longer the subject of a criminal investigation, she said the senator expected the ethics committee to quickly follow the Justice Department's example and conclude its investigation.
“Senator Ensign has a desire to continue his hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada,” he said.
Cheshire’s appeal will point to Twitter
There were half a dozen of them "chatting" in the rows of the courtroom.
Minute by minute, they sent reports of the terrifying testimony via Twitter.
In the end, the defense said, there were more than 140,000 Twitter messages about the process that addressed the rape and children tied to their beds in a house that was set on fire.
On Thursday, the widely followed trial of Steven J. Hayes, who was convicted of the murder of three members of a family in Cheshire, Connecticut, is ready to reach an official ending, with the judge's death sentence being passed by the jury.
But Mr. Hayes’ lawyers have filed court papers outlining the arguments of appeals that will likely occupy the courts for years.
One of the most provocative claims that intense reports on the process, including the widespread use of Twitter by mass media journalists, created “a circus atmosphere,” and such widespread and immediate saturation with exasperating details caused public passions to exert an inappropriate influence on the jury.
The claim could force appeal judges to deal with the question of whether the new technology requires new rules in the courtroom.
“According to what I experienced during this process, I think there is a real danger that the inclusion of new technology in the courtroom is affecting the individual’s rights to have a fair trial,” said Thomas J. Ullmann, Chief Defense Attorney.
First-instance judge Jon C. Blue of the State Supreme Court laconically rejected the lawsuits in a ruling last week, saying the media were "meticulously controlled" and that there was no evidence that the jury had been taken by passion.
But it probably won’t be the last word on the subject.
For decades, appeals courts have recognized that coverage of celebrity cases can raise questions about the impartiality of a process.
In a historic 1966 ruling, the U.S. Supreme Court revoked the conviction of a Cleveland osteopath, Dr. Sam Sheppard, for the murder of his wife, stating in his decision, in the Sheppard vs. Maxwell case, that there was "a carnival atmosphere in the media communication process."
It is believed that the crime had been inspired by the television show and the film "The Fugitive".
Some lawyers said that the appeals courts that examined Mr. Hayes' conviction half a century later might be intrigued by the argument that new rules might be needed to control the form of communication from the courtrooms, something unimaginable at the time of Dr. Sheppard's case.
"There is a general cause for concern about the impact of new media" in high-profile processes, said John J. Donohue III, a professor at the Stanford School of Law, who studied the death penalty in Connecticut and wrote a report saying it was arbitrarily imposed.
Professor Donohue said some appellate judges might be intrigued by the idea that limiting immediate communication from courtrooms could make the trials more fair.
The issue of Twitter is just one of many topics outlined by Hayes’ lawyers, which will likely be discussed for years, delaying an execution.
Defence lawyers also claim, for example, that Hayes may have been harmed when Judge Blue refused to allow them to test the reactions of potential juries, showing them scary photographs of the crime scene during jury selection.
Some jurors have said they were horrified by the photographs of the victims, 48-year-old Jennifer Hawke-Petit, and their daughters, 17-year-old Hayley and 11-year-old Michaela.
Defence lawyers say they will also question the constitutionality of the death penalty and will argue that the judge incorrectly removed a jury that had criticized the prosecutors, and that he had incorrectly pressed for a verdict for his strange decision to order the jury to deliberate over a weekend.
The jurors were not kidnapped.
But their arguments about the effect of intense process coverage can attract most of the interest.
They observed in a rejection of the verdict filed last month that the case dominated the news in Connecticut and was discussed during the election campaign by candidates for governor and the U.S. Senate.
They argued that the media were continuously throwing wood into the fire of emotion over the case.
"The daily agglomeration of media tweets, cameras and reporters outside the court," the lawyers wrote, "was something never seen here in New Haven and perhaps throughout the state."
Their focus on Tweeter coverage is controversial.
In some interviews, some journalists said that the complaint about the fact that the immediate news was more important than the reports delivered more slowly, was a playful vision that would make the court's policy on coverage control weak in future trials.
But some lawyers said the appeal courts were often attracted to the arguments on the adaptation required in the courts due to social and technological changes.
Hayes' lawyers are pressuring for that claim.
In their writing, they referred to the 1966 Supreme Court decision, which revokes Dr. Sheppard's conviction due to the coverage of the trial, and made it clear that they would require the new media to require new rules.
"This case," they wrote, "represents the Sheppard vs. Maxwell case of the 21st century."
Can civilization build a bridge to unite divisions?
After a notable campaign for invectiveness and negativity, this week has triggered a bit of civicism in Washington.
Is it a prelude to a genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick return to the party fight in the capital?
The Tuesday meeting between President Obama and Congress leaders did not produce any progress on the major issues that should be dealt with during the outgoing session.
But as everyone says, it was at least a courteous discussion about the differences between the two sides, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than being another empty episode to win partisan points.
Wednesday’s public meeting of the president’s deficit committee was equally civilized, despite the political differences that persist between the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months generated mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap that still separates members.
That is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Both sides are now in a trial period, probing each other to identify signs of cooperativeism and commitment, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed partisan war.
The reason why the Tuesday meeting and subsequent evaluations of the meeting by the participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too large and are deeply rooted to suggest any rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it’s taxes, expenses, health care or social assistance, the two sides are on opposite poles.
Anyway, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed with respect to the way things are said," said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
“They are inevitable after the election.
Elections arouse partisan passions, which then extinct.
That's good."
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the outgoing session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of this.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all of the reductions, either permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a commitment to expand unemployment subsidies, probably because Republicans can’t believe they’re in favor of tax cuts for the rich, denying unemployment subsidies for the unemployed workers.
After Tuesday’s meeting at the White House, there is greater optimism for a possible deal on these issues during the outgoing session, along with the ratification of the new START nuclear disarmament pact (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty).
But William Galston, of the Brookings Institution, warns that successful cooperation on the pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continuous bipartisanism when the new 112th Congress meets in January.
He said, on the contrary, that it is very likely and even inevitable, that a period of disagreement begins.
“After the things that have to be done are carried out, psychology will in the short term reverse the situation to a confrontation,” he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civilization can lead to true cooperation.
“I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as a test for the 2012 main event,” he said.
The reasons have much to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the Tea Party voters, who contributed decisively to its creation.
As much as Republican leaders are aware of the dangers of exaggerating their position, they know that they must try to keep their promises to cut state spending and repeal the new health law.
Those backing lines are already clearly seen in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the deficit committee, which include reform of the tax code and the increase in some taxes and the retirement age, and the cut in expenses.
Co-Presidents Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have been in charge of one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have forcefully introduced the issue of the deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes on the 18-member committee to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and have been struggling to get close to that figure.
The greatest resilience is among elected panel officials, suggesting that in tax matters at least at present there is little basis or desire for commitment.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the Republicans of the White House and those of Congress.
The first will happen next year in the form of partisan shocks, when Republicans challenge Obama on budget, taxes and medical care, followed by a period of increased bilateral cooperation.
What would cause the change?
The public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a dead end, as it happened in 1995, then both parties will closely observe the reaction of the people.
Anyone who thinks they’re losing will likely change course and look for commitment.
However, this can be an optimistic view.
Partism and polarization are now larger than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a bigger ideological gap between Obama and Congressional Republicans than there was between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as the mere prelude to a more transcendental election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilization shown this week can be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort from both sides to find common points on issues that still divide them.
A leaked U.S. document portrays Moscow as the paradise of corruption
Control of the city is in the hands of a “cleptocracy,” and leaves part of the bribes and protection money that it raises directly to the Kremlin, the U.S. Embassy in Russia reported in February.
It was reported that both the police and the Federal Security Service are handling huge blackmail systems, which helps explain the high cost of life in Moscow.
They raise money not only from legitimate businesses, but also from organized criminal groups.
Every stratum of the bureaucracy, what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called “vertical authority,” takes its part as money rises on the scale.
The note, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was published by WikiLeaks on its website on Wednesday.
The note is based on sources whose names have been censored.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still the mayor of Moscow, and blamed him for much of the corruption.
President Dmitry Medvedev fired him in October, but there has been little evidence of a cleanup since then.
Luzhkov and his wife, Yelena Baturina, who owns a major construction company, have systematically denied corruption allegations over the years, and he has won several libel claims over such allegations.
In September, when asked on a Russian television channel about a documentary that suggested it was corrupt, he said: “It’s a madness, a patria, an annoyance.”
According to polls, Russians overwhelmingly believe that their society is corrupt.
But it is unusual to find the details explained in detail, as they were in the embassy report, and it is unheard of that it is the diplomats of a foreign country who do so.
“The direct links of the Moscow city government with crime have led some to call it ‘dysfunctional’, and to assert that the government functions more as a cleptocracy than as a government,” the statement said.
“The criminal elements enjoy a ‘krysha’ (a term of the criminal world and the mafia literally meaning ‘roof’ or protection) that transcends the police, the Federal Security Service (SFS), the Ministry of Home Affairs (MVD), and the prosecutor’s office, as well as all sectors of the city bureaucracy.
“Analysts identify a three-level structure in Moscow’s criminal world.”
"Luzhkov is at the highest."
“The SFS, the MVD and the militia are on the second level.”
“Finally, common criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level.”
“This is an inefficient system in which criminal groups fill a gap in some areas, because the city does not provide some services.”
The report states that the SFS collects money from the largest companies, and that the police are targeting small businesses.
A source, the report said, explained that “Moscow business owners understand that it is best to get the protection of MVD and SFS (rather than organized crime groups) as they not only have more weapons, resources and power than criminal groups, but they are also protected by law.”
“For this reason, protection against criminal gangs is no longer a priority.”
The note notes that while money collection is complete, protection may be irregular; even those who pay are subject to arrest.
Those who don’t pay quickly find their businesses closed by one pretext or another.
Medvedev has spoken several times about the fight against corruption, but has confessed that he has made little progress.
The embassy note reports about men taking suitcases, probably full of cash, within the Kremlin itself.
"In its fight against corruption, Medvedev has to rely on bureaucrats," said Georgy Satarov, director of the Indem expert group in Moscow, in a recent interview.
"But he is a part of this bureaucracy."
“He does not belong to a political class, because there is no political class in Russia anymore.”
Without politics, without opposition, without a separation of powers, he said, corruption is inevitable.
At the national level, Indem estimates that corruption costs Russia more than <0x24>300 billion a year.
In a recent survey of global perceptions of corruption conducted by the non-governmental organization Transparency International, the country was ranked 154th (countries are ranked at least the most corrupt).
The disclosure of the U.S. Embassy note, which did not occur until late in Moscow, will surely cause disgust within the Russian government, and even though Luzhkov may be blamed for Moscow’s weaknesses, could be an opportunity for the Kremlin to argue that it is solving the problem.
Interviewed for CNN by Larry King, Putin suggested that WikiLeaks documents could be lies and reacted furiously to a revelation claiming that U.S. diplomats called him Batman and Medvedev Robin.
“The truth of the matter is that this is related to our interaction, which is an important factor of domestic policies in this country,” he said.
“But to be honest with you, we don’t suspect that this would have been done with such arrogance, with such pressure and, you know, that it was done in such an immoral way.”
The veterans of the Red Jemers forced to face the past
In a weakly illuminated concrete classroom, with stained walls and debris, the director of Anlong Veng High School reminded the man who had built it, the last leader of the Ta Mok Red Jemers.
"Here everyone loves Ta Mok".
“He was a good leader and worried about his people,” said 42-year-old Sreng Kor Ma.
Known as "the Carnicer" for his brutality during the rule of the Red Jemers, the commander remains popular in this remote former Red Jemer fortress in northwestern Cambodia, where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructures, and where thousands of ex-soldiers of the organization still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Red Jemers surrendered to the government, long-held loyalty is finally being challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local forum for truth and reconciliation allowed the victims to publicly confront the people who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed here a high school textbook that for the first time teaches the history of the Red Jemers to the children of their former soldiers.
And in July, a United Nations and Cambodia joint court issued the first sentence of a former Red Jemer member, sentenced to 35 years in prison to the former head of the known torture center, Tuol Sleng, Kaing Khek Iev.
With each of those events, anxiety has grown among the veterans of the Anlong Veng Red Jemers, complicating efforts for reconciliation and their attempts to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
"There is resentment and fear among the former Red Jemers, but they can do nothing," said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodian Documentation Center, an independent organization investigating the regime.
“For them, life under the Red Jemers was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil.”
"This is generating divisions within families."
During the government of the Cambodian Red Jemers, between 1975 and 1979, about 1.7 million people were executed or died of starvation, illness or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrown the government led by Pol Pot in 1979, the remnants of the regime and its military fled to the Cambodian border with Thailand.
There they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last movement that surrendered in December 1998.
As Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerrilla war from their bases in the mountains and jungles of western Cambodia, Ta Mok grew followers in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace deal led to the country’s first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Red Jemer fighters began to desert to the government, culminating in the surrenders of Ieng Sary in 1996, and Nuon Chea and Khieuphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had resisted, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the nearby Dangrek Mountains.
He died in a Phnom Penh prison in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Without the support of their benefactors, the oldest Red Jemer fighters fell into the absolute misery that is common in rural Cambodia, and many feel nostalgia for the movement.
Although a few Red Jemer elite officials retained their local administrative positions in exchange for laying down their weapons, the Racial Soldiers remain poor and unskilled farmers.
“These people have gained little benefit after surrender,” said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which offers public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
"They have incorporated the regime's utopian agrarian ideology."
“They were created without any concept of doing business.”
Sister Lim, 55, who joined the Red Jemers as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle near Anlong Veng before dedicating himself to life as a poor rice farmer in 1998.
“Life with the Red Jemers was good,” he said.
"Ta Mok gave everyone to eat."
“But now life is difficult because we have to self-sufficiency.”
The current court of the Red Jemers has also caused concerns here.
Earlier next year, the court is expected to begin prosecuting Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Red Jemer minister.
The court's mandate is to prosecute the leading leaders and those most responsible for the crimes, but it has not said whether it will prosecute cases in addition to those four.
This didn’t help much to calm the fears in Anlong Veng.
Recent media speculation has focused on 64-year-old Im Chaem, who was a district chief in the Banteay Meanchey province during the Red Sea government in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at the Cambodian Documentation Center that she had overseen the construction of the Trapeang Thma dam, a project in which thousands of forced workers are believed to have died.
During a boring late afternoon, Im Chaem returned from working in the fields to his home on wooden pilots on a ground road outside Anlong Veng.
When the sun threw long shadows over the dry pasture, Im Chaem refused to talk about his past in the Red Jemers.
She said that if the court called her, she would not be present.
"Cambodia is in peace and stability," he said.
“If there are more trials, there will be war.”
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who deserted the Red Sea in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that there will be instability if the court pursues more suspects, even though experts and historians question it.
“Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past,” he said.
But facing the past is exactly what Cambodia must do to move forward, said Chhang Youk, of the documentation center.
“Reconciliation, according to Khmer, is to reunite the broken pieces,” he said.
“It is our duty to gather these broken pieces so that we can understand.”
The center produced the first government-approved 75-page textbook on the Red Sheep, called A History of Democratic Kampuchea.
It was distributed in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the high school history textbook of the Ministry of Education, which contains less than four pages about the Red Jemers.
As in most of Cambodia, the young people of Anlong Veng know little details about the Red Jemers, despite the city’s link to the regime.
Touche Valeak, a 19-year-old student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new textbook helped students understand an important part of their story.
But his parents reacted with skepticism when he took the book home to study.
“My family rejects many parts of the textbook and the court,” he said.
“They have suspicions because they are not sure how many people the court will prosecute.”
Such resistance has made the reconciliation process complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But public forums, the textbook and the court are beginning to produce an impact, he said.
Anyway, here the Red Jemers retain a powerful charm.
In the Dangrek Mountains, a path with too many weeds and covered with disposable plastic bags leads to a black hole rectangle covered by a sheet oxidized roof.
Pol Pot's body was burned here on a lot of tyres after his death in 1998.
