Finally, the UEFA disciplinary committee has sanctioned team coach José Mourinho with two matches, and with different economic amounts to the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the unwritten but followed rules of this sport.
Part of the debate that has arisen in the reported case is due to the fact that it has been starred by a team of the Real Madrid entity (who in his hymn presumes of nobility and honor, and who in the past has fined his players for similar acts) and the orchestrated dramatization, apparently by Mourinho, who added a technical story of his own.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of behavior not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions commit fraud; for in fact, they are actions respectful of the sport regulation, but they seem to evade its meaning.
The question lies in examining the type of damage to the sporting spirit.
One of the assets of the sporting spirit is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions was not put in danger, i.e. there was no violent play.
Another of these assets that is referred to with the clean play is to prevent the team of the offending players from unjustly taking advantage of the opposing team, which did not happen either.
Now, the paradox of the action of the Real Madrid players is that it did not fit what we normally characterize as a trap or fraud, because its violation of the rules was not done in secret to try to avoid the penalty, but precisely its action tried to be the most obvious in order to receive the penalty from the referee.
They waited and gladly accepted the penalty.
Another question is what kind of advantage do offenders get in the deliberate faults examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that it is not placed in a disadvantage to the rival nor is profit obtained in the same game, since obviously the result of the action involves leaving the team itself with fewer players.
And it’s also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club will not be able to count on those players.
The advantage, of course, is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that can threaten their participation in a future game.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indetermination, since the team can be eliminated at the first change, and with this action players meet a penalty match and move to the second card cycle, in which the card accumulation suspension occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, to go through rounds, it's not so clear that it's an advantage.
In short, these actions do not go against the sporting spirit, of which it is part to make strategic decisions that promote to make the most of what the rules allow.
In the assumption that we occupy, the players did not act to evade the application of the penalty (this would be a clear case of law fraud), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without taking the punishment or escaping it.
Although the border between ingenuity and law fraud is widespread, this time I think it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises from two factors: because it was two self-expulsions and the way in which the transmission of the direction to provoke them was carried out.
The damage caused to the beginnings of the sport by these actions is not so ethical as aesthetic.
