EU changes rules to obtain visas
Individuals must visit the Visa Applicants Service Centres prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cost will be lower and the waiting time will be lower.
As of January 10, 2011, the procedure for processing a visa at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
With the new procedure, most applicants will have to go to the Visa Applicants Service Centres (ASC) before their interview in the Consular Section.
ASC staff will take the applicant’s biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for applicants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, no longer will it be necessary to make a payment to arrange the appointment, another payment to process the visa application and more so that the courier service delivers the document.
The applicant will only make a single payment covering the three services.
The current rate will remain unchanged: the equivalent of <0x24>140 for a tourist visa, <0x24>150 for case-by-case visas (including visas for temporary workers) and <0x24>390 for trader and investor visas.
People who wish to renew their visa will not have to go to an interview with the Consular Officer, but will only go to the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and take their fingerprints.
Because biometric information will be taken from the ASC, applicants requiring a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain in the ASC less time than in the past.
Similarly, those applying for visas at the Consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the additional service fee of <0x24>26.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, visit the following page http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visa-FAQs.html
