A 10-year-old boy ingested 81 different chemicals on a day, according to a study published Wednesday by the association Generations Futures (the old movement for rights and respect for future generations).
The association, which warns that its results "have no significant statistical value given the limited number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem treated", acquired in Oise and Paris supermarkets between July and September the foods a child of about ten years consumed on four days and ten days.
These meals taken as a model, which comply with official recommendations (five parts of fresh fruits and vegetables, three of dairy products and 1.5 liters of water a day), as well as treats, were examined in laboratories in search of chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other contaminants.
The balance of the plate is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are classified as possible or likely carcinogens and five substances classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances likely to act as endocrine disruptors (PE), according to studies by various institutions such as the International Center for Research on Cancer.
“While, in almost all cases, the legal limits for each of the chemicals are not exceeded individually, our study clearly shows that consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic and/or PE contaminants is troubling,” the association notes.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three considered safe carcinogenic residues, as well as about twenty residues that can harm the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, intended as an attempt for the school, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to Kenyan greens, including in food, where the study has detected traces of a potent insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, Russian fillet, canned tuna, and even bread bar or gum were tainted with pesticides and other chemicals.
In the tap water, the analyses discovered the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon roll was the most "nutrient" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the analysis of the plastic dish used to heat the food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The final risk these "pollutant cocktails" generate for the consumer "is probably underestimated," the study says.
The Europe Ecology-Les Verts Alliance (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed to apply a moratorium on the use of pesticides to curb "the rise of civilization-associated diseases".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (AESA) indicated the presence of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereals.
